          <h1 className="text-4xl font-bold text-gray-900 mt-2">AI 2026: Safe Multi‑Agent Approvals — Blueprint</h1>
          <p className="text-lg text-gray-600 mt-4">Risk‑tiered approvals, budgets, and policy‑as‑code guardrails enabling safe multi‑agent collaboration in production.</p>
        </header>

        <div className="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
          <h2>Why Approvals Matter in Multi‑Agent Systems</h2>
          <p>As agents coordinate, compound risks emerge across tools, data, and actions. Explicit approvals ensure sensitive actions are gated by policy, context, and evidence of safety.</p>

          <h2>Risk‑Tiered Actions</h2>
          <ul>
            <li>Classify actions into tiers (low, medium, high) by impact, blast radius, and reversibility.</li>
            <li>Map each tier to required controls: pre‑checks, reviewer roles, evidence, and rollback plans.</li>
          </ul>

          <h2>Approvals as Policy‑as‑Code</h2>
          <p>Codify approver roles, thresholds, and exceptions. Validate using evals and attach evidence bundles to every approval for auditability.</p>

          <h2>Budgets and Quotas</h2>
          <p>Enforce spend limits, concurrency caps, and rate limits per agent, tenant, and tool. Surface budget breaches to operations dashboards and auto‑throttle when exceeded.</p>
          
          <h2>Operationalizing in CI/CD</h2>
          <p>Wire approvals into release pipelines with evaluation gates. Block promotion until safety scorecards pass and required approvals are attached.</p>

          <h2>Runtime Guardrails</h2>
          <p>Apply runtime policy checks on tool invocations. For high‑risk intents, require human‑in‑the‑loop confirmation or secondary agent review.</p>
        </div>

        <footer className="mt-12 flex items-center justify-between">
